text: Loma Prieta was a major quake (M6.9) but was too far from SF (60mi aways) to cause strong ground shaking. By comparison, 1906 was M7.9 and epicenter was much closer to SF.  In 89, ground shook for ~10 seconds. In 1906, ground shook for nearly 60 seconds.

text: The Pier 43 Ferry Arch makes a great photo op but in its heyday, trains used it as an access point to haul railcars to & from ferries for the Beltline Railroad, which ran along the entire Embarcadero. text: In 1865, side-wheel steamboats hauled goods from SF to gold rush river towns. Steamboats leaving the Broadway Wharf (btwn Piers 7 & 9) got to Sacramento or Stockton in 9-10 hrs.
